# Git Workflow and Versioning

## Overview

Treat commits as save points and history as documentation. Keep changes small, reviewable, and reversible.

## When to Use

Always. Every code change flows through git.

## Core Principles

### Trunk-Based Development (recommended)

Keep `main` deployable. Prefer short-lived feature branches (merge within days). Prefer feature flags over long-lived branches for incomplete work.

### Commit Early, Commit Often

Pattern: implement slice → verify → commit → next slice. Do not accumulate large uncommitted changes.

### Atomic Commits

Each commit does one logical thing. Separate refactors from features when they are independent.

### Descriptive Messages

Explain **why**, not only **what**. Suggested form:

```
<type>: <short description>

<optional body>
```

**Types:** `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`

### Size Changes

Target ~100 lines per logical commit/PR when practical; split very large diffs.

### Branch Naming (when branching)

`feature/…`, `fix/…`, `chore/…`, `refactor/…`

## Pre-Commit Hygiene

Before committing:

- Review `git diff` / `git diff --staged`
- Ensure no secrets (passwords, tokens, `.env` contents) in the diff — this repo ignores `.env` / `.env.local` via `.gitignore`; do not force-add them
- Run `npm run lint` and `npx tsc --noEmit`; run `npm run build` before merges or when changes are broad

## Generated / Ignored Files

- Commit `package-lock.json`, Prisma migrations, and project-expected artifacts
- Do not commit `node_modules/`, `.next/`, `.env`, `.env.local`

## Change Summary (for agents)

After substantive work, a short summary helps review:

- What files changed and why
- What was intentionally out of scope
- Any risks or follow-ups

## Common rationalizations

| Rationalization | Reality |
|---|---|
| "I'll commit when the feature is done" | Giant commits are hard to review, debug, revert. |
| "The message doesn't matter" | History is documentation for humans and agents. |
| "I'll squash it all later" | Prefer clean incremental commits from the start. |
| "I'll split this change later" | Split before review/merge, not after. |

## Red Flags

- Messages like "fix", "update", "misc"
- Formatting-only churn mixed with behavior changes in the same commit without need
- Committing secrets or local env files
- Force-pushing shared branches without team agreement

## Verification (each commit)

- [ ] One logical change (or clearly related set)
- [ ] Message follows conventions and explains intent
- [ ] Lint/typecheck (and build when appropriate) pass
- [ ] No secrets in the diff

